From aad62153c971cb93f0953490b2513b5b1aeeeaff Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Mon, 22 Jun 2026 13:36:03 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Guard against NULL path in vchroot-based path syscalls

A forked child building a Homebrew formula under Darling takes a SIGSEGV
during dyld two-level-namespace symbol binding. The crash is a genuine
strcpy(dst, NULL) -> strlen(NULL): sys_lstat64() copies its `path`
argument into the vchroot expand buffer with strcpy() before any NULL
check, and dyld's bind path calls lstat64(NULL) (rax=0 deref in
_platform_strlen, fault addr=0x0).

sys_lstat() and several siblings already guard `if (!path) return -EFAULT;`,
but the guard was applied inconsistently -- 15 path-taking syscalls in the
emulation layer do strcpy(vc.path, path) (and linkat additionally
strcpy(vc2.path, link)) with no NULL check, so each is a latent
strcpy(NULL) crash reachable from any guest passing a NULL path.

Add the same `if (!path) return -EFAULT;` guard (matching the existing
guarded functions) to every unguarded site:
  lstat64, statfs64, utimes, chdir, chmod_extended, fchmodat, fchownat,
  lchown, linkat (path+link), mknod, readlinkat, truncate, unlinkat,
  getxattr, listxattr.

EFAULT is the documented errno for a bad path pointer; returning it
matches the existing guards and POSIX. Files that did not already pull in
<sys/errno.h> get the include (mirroring the guarded siblings).
---
 .../emulation/src/xnu_syscall/bsd/impl/stat/lstat.c          | 5 ++++-
 .../emulation/src/xnu_syscall/bsd/impl/stat/statfs.c         | 5 +++++
